Here's a basic example of a Discord bot using Discord.js v14 that has a `/ban` slash command:

```javascript
const { Client, GatewayIntentBits, Permissions } = require('discord.js');
const client = new Client({ intents: [GatewayIntentBits.Guilds, GatewayIntentBits.GuildMessages, GatewayIntentBits.Member] });

client.commands.create({
  name: 'ban',
  description: 'Bans a member from the server',
  options: [
    {
      name: 'user',
      description: 'The user to ban',
      type: 'user',
      required: true
    },
    {
      name: 'reason',
      description: 'The reason for the ban',
      type: 'string',
      required: false
    }
  ],
  defaultMemberPermissions: Permissions.Bitfield.fromBits(Permissions.FLAGS.BAN_MEMBERS),
  async execute(interaction) {
    const user = interaction.options.getUser('user');
    const reason = interaction.options.getString('reason', 'No reason provided');
    const member = interaction.guild.members.cache.get(user.id);

    if (!member) {
      await interaction.reply(`Cannot find user ${user.username}#${user.discriminator} in this server.`);
      return;
    }

    try {
      await member.ban({ reason: reason });
      await interaction.reply(`Banned ${user.username}#${user.discriminator} for ${reason}`);
    } catch (error) {
      await interaction.reply(`Error banning the user: ${error}`);
    }
  }
});

client.login('YOUR_DISCORD_BOT_TOKEN');

// Register commands (must be done after client creation)
await client.registry.registerApplicationsCommandsJSONFilePath Path('path/to/commands.json');
// (Alternatively, you can register commands programmatically like shown above)
// Since v14, JSON file registration is preferred for production use.
// Make sure to replace 'path/to/commands.json' with your actual file path.
```

Note:

- Make sure to install the necessary packages by running `npm install discord.js` or `yarn add discord.js`.
- Replace `YOUR_DISCORD_BOT_TOKEN` with your actual Discord bot token.
- Create a `commands.json` file in the same directory with the command definition in the following format (alternatively register programmatically as shown above):

```json
[
  {
    "name": "ban",
    "type": 1, // slash_command
    "description": "Bans a member from the server",
    "options": [...], // same options as in the code above
  }
]
```

This code sets up a `/ban` command that takes an optional reason. It bans the specified user and replies to the interaction with the result. Make sure to adjust the error handling to fit your needs.}

